 a row last Sunday night.<br>
<br>
It was amazingly done- such beautiful storytelling. It really put you in the time and space, and showed the impact the religion created in less than one hundred years. The map that showed how far the message spread in such a short time was amazing.<br>
<br>
I was amazed to learn how much of modern medicine was based on the germ theory propulgated by Islamic clerics who were given stipends to study- without regards to religion- every day, because it was a central tenet of Islam that all knowledge gained in that way is for the greater good.<br>
<br>
Also- did you know that Baghdad was responsible for much of the paper used in the ancient world- they adopted paper over parchment, because it was cheaper and easier to get, and the Muslims made endless copies of all that they learned, and passed that knowledge on to other cultures freely? Many Christian and Jewish scholars would come to Baghdad to share information.<br>
<br>
Also, and I thought this was fascinating- did you know that much of the garments used by the Catholic churches in Europe, from around 1000AD were made on Muslim looms, and in some of the most respected Christian paintings in the world, the Virgin is shown holding Jesus wearing robes finely embroidered with the Islamic symbols for &quot;there is but one G-d, his name is Allah&quot;....<br>
<br>
How 'bout that for a factoid or two?<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :eek --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/eek.gif ALT=":eek"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
Jessica<br>
